==Fleet==
[[File:British Airways tails lined up at LHR Terminal 5B Iwelumo .jpg|thumb|British Airways [[747-400]] and 777 aircraft at [[London Heathrow Terminal 5]]]]
With the exception of the [[Boeing 707]] and early [[Boeing 747]] variants from BOAC, British Airways inherited a mainly UK-built fleet of aircraft when it was formed in 1974. The airline introduced the [[Boeing 737]] and [[Boeing 757]] into the fleet in the 1980s, followed by the Boeing 747-400, [[Boeing 767]] and [[Boeing 777]] in the 1990s. BA is now the largest operator of Boeing 747-400s, with 55 in its fleet.<ref name = BAP/><ref name = EOP9/> When Boeing builds an aircraft for British Airways, it is allocated the [[List of Boeing customer codes|customer code]] ''36'', which appears in their aircraft designation as a suffix, such as 737-436.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caa.co.uk/application.aspx?catid=60&pagetype=65&appid=1&mode=summary&aircrafttype=Boeing&owner=British%20Airways|title=CAA Aircraft Register (Boeing aircraft registered to British Airways)|work=Civil Aviation Authority|accessdate=5 September 2009}}</ref>

In 2007 British Airways placed its first order for 777-200ER aircraft, purchasing four for fleet expansion for around US$800&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-30158167_ITM|title=Boeing and British Airways complete deal for four 777-200ERs; Boeing 777 is logical complement to British Airways' wide-body fleet|work=M2 Presswire|date=28 March 2007|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref> BA's first 777s were fitted with [[General Electric GE90]] engines, but BA switched to [[Rolls-Royce Trent 800]]s for subsequent aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60879579.html|title=Rolls-Royce lands US jets deal|work=Birmingham Evening Mail|accessdate=18 August 1998}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-06/rolls-royce-wins-british-airways-order-for-trent-plane-engines.html|title=British Airways Picks Troubled Rolls Engine for A380s |author=Howard Mustoe, Steve Rothwell |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=15 July 2013}}</ref>

[[File:A380 & Red Arrows - RIAT 2013.jpg|thumb|left|British Airways' first Airbus A380, accompanied by the [[Red Arrows]] at 2013 [[Royal International Air Tattoo]]]]
Later in 2007 BA announced their order of thirty-six new long-haul aircraft, including twelve [[Airbus A380]]s and twenty-four [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner]]s.<ref name='baorder'>{{Cite news|title=BA opts for A380 and Dreamliner|date=27 September 2007|publisher=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7015621.stm|accessdate=27 September 2007}}</ref> [[Rolls-Royce Trent]] engines were again selected for both orders with Trent 900s powering the A380s and Trent 1000s powering the 787s. The Boeing 787s will replace fourteen of British Airways' Boeing 767 fleet, while the Airbus A380s will replace twenty of BA's oldest Boeing 747-400s and will most likely be used to increase capacity on key routes from London Heathrow.

On 1 August 2008, BA announced orders for six Boeing 777-300ERs and options for four more as an interim measure to cover for delays over the deliveries of their 787-8/9s. Of the six that have been ordered, four will be leased and two will be fully acquired by British Airways.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/money/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=&xml=/money/2008/08/01/bcnba301.xml|title=BA warns that ticket prices will jump as routes are axed|last=Dunkley|first=Jamie|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 August 2008|accessdate=1 August 2008 | location=London}}</ref> 

On 22 April 2013, IAG confirmed that it had signed a memorandum of understanding to order 18 A350-1000 aircraft for British Airways, with an option for a further 18. The aircraft would replace some of the airline's fleet of Boeing 747-400s.<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/iag-to-order-18-a350s-for-ba-384980/ IAG to order 18 A350s for BA]</ref> Options for 18 Boeing 787 aircraft, part of the original contract signed in 2007, have been converted into firm orders for delivery between 2017 and 2021.<ref>{{Citation | title = Airbus A350 for British Airways | journal = Airliner World | pages = p5 | date = June 2013 | year = 2013 }}</ref>

On 26 June 2013, British Airways took delivery of its first 787s. The aircraft began operations to Toronto on 1 September 2013, and began service to Newark on 1 October 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/09/02/ba_dreamliner_completes_inaugural_londontoronto_flight.html|title=BA Dreamliner completes inaugural London-Toronto flight |last=Ellison|first=Marc|work=Toronto Star|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> BA's first A380 was delivered on 4 July 2013;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-23177384|title=BA's first A380 superjumbo arrives at Heathrow airport|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> three are planned to be in service by the end of 2013.<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Woodman |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/ba-reveals-airbus-a380-superjumbo-flight-plans-8405961.html |title=BA reveals Airbus A380 superjumbo flight plans |publisher=The Independent |date=11 December 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> It began regular services to Los Angeles on 24 September 2013, followed by Hong Kong on 22 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wall |first=Robert |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-05/british-airways-to-operate-first-a380s-to-los-angeles-hong-kong.html |title=British Airways to Fly First A380s to Los Angeles, Hong Kong |publisher=Bloomberg |date= |accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> Services to Johannesburg will follow in February 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businesstraveller.com/news/ba-to-fly-a380-to-johannesburg |title=British Airways to fly A380 to Johanneburg |date=24 July 2013 |publisher=Business Traveller |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>

The majority (77%) of the British Airways fleet is either powered by [[Rolls-Royce Group PLC|Rolls-Royce]] or [[International Aero Engines|IAE]] alliance [[Aircraft engines|engines]], of which Rolls-Royce was a major contributor. The remaining 23% of the fleet is equally divided between [[GE Aviation|General Electric]] and the [[CFM International]] consortium.<ref name="G-INFO" />

The combined International Airlines Group entity, that BA is now a part of, operates around 400 aircraft, carries over 62&nbsp;million passengers annually, and serves more than 200 destinations.<ref name = BAIM/>

As of November 2013, the British Airways fleet includes the following aircraft:<ref name="G-INFO">{{cite web|url=http://www.caa.co.uk/application.aspx?catid=60&pagetype=65&appid=1&mode=summary&owner=British%20Airways |title=United Kingdom Civil Aircraft Register |work=United Kingdom Civil Aviation Authority |date=24 November 2013 |accessdate= 25 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishairways.com/travel/bafleet/public/en_gb |title=British Airways Fleet Facts |publisher=British Airways |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>

